HOUSE JOINT RESOLUTION 1050
By Martin G
A RESOLUTION to honor Sam Houston on the occasion of his
birthday.
WHEREAS, it is fitting that we remember those individuals whose lives shaped the
history of this State and nation; and
WHEREAS, Samuel Houston, known as Sam Houston, was born on March 2, 1793, in
Rockbridge County, Virginia; and
WHEREAS, Sam Houston moved to Tennessee as a young man in 1807, settling in the
eastern part of the State near Maryville in Blount County; and
WHEREAS, as a teenager, Mr. Houston left his family and spent three years on
Hiwassee Island at the confluence of the Tennessee and Hiwassee rivers; during that time, he
was adopted into a Cherokee Indian family and received the name "The Raven" from the chief,
and he began his lifetime fascination with classical literature, including Homer's Iliad and The
Odyssey; and
WHEREAS, Sam Houston returned to Maryville in 1812 and opened a one-room
schoolhouse, remarking years later that as a teacher, "I experienced a higher feeling of dignity
and self-satisfaction than from any office or honor which I have since held."; and
WHEREAS, during the War of 1812, Mr. Houston served bravely under General Andrew
Jackson, particularly distinguishing himself at 1814's Battle of Horseshoe Bend, where he was
severely wounded yet continued to fight, receiving wounds that would hinder him for the rest of
his life; and
WHEREAS, Sam Houston developed a close friendship and mentorship with Andrew
Jackson, who supported his political rise, including his election to the United States House of
Representatives from Tennessee and later as Governor of Tennessee in 1827; and
