- 1 -

WHEREAS, Mr. Houston went on to achieve great glory in leading our sister state of
Texas to independence, signing the Texas Declaration of Independence on his birthday, March
2, serving as commander of the Texas Army, and decisively defeating Mexican forces led by
General Antonio Lopez de Santa Anna at the Battle of San Jacinto in 1836 in a battle that,
although his forces were greatly outnumbered, lasted only eighteen minutes; he then became
the first president of the Republic of Texas and later served as a United States Senator from
Texas and as Governor of Texas; and
WHEREAS, Sam Houston is the only person ever to be elected as governor of two
states; and
WHEREAS, a strong supporter of the Union throughout his life, Mr. Houston opposed
secession during the lead-up to the Civil War, and, when Texas seceded in 1861, he refused to
take an oath of allegiance to the Confederacy, allowing the Texas legislature to remove him
from office rather than betray his principles and bring civil strife to his adopted state; and
WHEREAS, Sam Houston's actions during this pivotal moment in American history
reflect the strength of his convictions and the depth of his dedication to public service; now,
therefore,
BE IT RESOLVED BY THE HOUSE OF REPRESENTATIVES OF THE ONE HUNDRED
FOURTEENTH GENERAL ASSEMBLY OF THE STATE OF TENNESSEE, THE SENATE
CONCURRING, that we honor Sam Houston on the occasion of his birthday, March 2,
recognize his distinguished service to the State of Tennessee and to the nation, and reflect
upon his enduring contributions to American history.
BE IT FURTHER RESOLVED, that an appropriate copy of this resolution be prepared
for presentation with this final clause omitted from such copy and upon proper request made to
the appropriate clerk, the language appearing immediately following the State seal appear
without House or Senate designation.
